Histogram of pH of wine faceted by quality

After wrapping the histogram of pH by quality, we can see pH is normally distributed across the quality 4,5,6,7. This means the amount of pH is not affected by the wine quality in those groups.

Density without transformation is nearly normally distributed, which means the samples resemble the population in a large extent.

The alcohol distribution is right skewed, meaning that its mean is higher than the median. In the next step, we try to log transform it to explore deeper.

As we see, even after the transformation of scale, alcohol is still right skewed .

Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

There are 1599 wines in the dataset with 12 features(fixed.acidity, volatile. acidity, citric acid, residual sugar, chlorides, free.sulfur.dioxide, total.sulfur.dioxide,density, alcohol, sulphates, quality). One variable quality is transormed into factor variable, quality.f with the following levels:

(worst)___________>(best) Quality: 3,4,5,6,7,8

Other observations: * There are 18 wines that have the highest quality and 10 the lowest. * Mean Ph is 3.31. * The distribution of sulphates is very similar to that of fixed acidity. * The maximum residual sugar is 15.5

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

The main features are quality and density. I like to determine what features determine the quality of a wine. I suspect density and some combinations of other variables can be used to build a predictive model to classify wine. ### What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your
investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

density, pH, alcohol, residual sugar and total sulfur dioxide likely contribute to the quality. I think density and pH and toatl sulfur dioxide contribute the most.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

I create a factor variable quality.f as a analysis metric since it is a categorical variable. The levels of quality are respresnted by the original int.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions?
Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form
of the data? If so, why did you do this?

I log transformed total.sulfur.dioxide and free.sulfur.dioxide which were previously right-skewed. The data after transformation is bimodal. For the free sulfur dioxide, it peaks around 2.0 and 2.8, while there is a gap between 1.2 and 1.4. For the total free dioxide, it peaks around 3.15 and 3.9 while there is a gap between 5.1 and 5.7. I did this to find underlying patterns of skewed data. I also log-transformed alcohol, yet the distributions before and after look alike.

We take a subset of wine excluding the the X and quality.f variables.

We see pH and fixed acidity have the highest negative correlation, followed by citric acid and fixed acidity. After some research, I found acid in wine is responsible for the crisp taste. However, the acids in the data have very low correlation with quality. So what feature is related to high quality?

After using a more clear visualization, we see alcohol has the highest correlation with quality. However, the correlation 0.48 is still not high enough. After research I know alcohol contributes to the flavour. Maybe the level of alcohol is related to the quality of wine?

The first plot shows overplotting. After adjustment by adding jitter and changing transparency, we still can see that the data is over-dispersed.

Density distribution is similar to that of alcohol.

We there is a clear positive relationship between fixed.acidity and density. In fact, the typical concentration of fixed acid in wine is 6000 mg/L, which is quite big, only second to Glycerol.

We can see pH is negatively related to citric acid. This no surprise since the higher the acid, the lower the pH.

Same trend has been observed in the plot of pH vs fixed acidity.

However, the trend is lost when we plot pH vs volatile acidity.
In general, We see there is a negative strong correlation between citric acid and pH which is not surprising since the more acidic a solution is, the lower pH it has. The same siuation applies to other acid metrics like fixed.acidity. However, volatile acidity doesn’t show such correlation.

Bivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the
investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in
the dataset?

There are no variables that have strong correlation with win quality. Regardless of quality, the variance in alcohol is high in each level. In the plot of quality vs alcohol, at each quality level the alcohol amount is spread out.

Based on the R^2 value, alcohol can only explain about 22.6%, yet other variable such as pH did a worse job.

It has been confirmed that fixed acidity and citric acid are negatively related to pH based on chemical domain knowledge. However, it is counterintuitive that volatile acidity doesn’t follow such trend and even has a positive correlation.
The correlation table justifies such behavior by showing that volatile acidity is negatively to other two acidity metrics.

Density has a distribution across quality groups similar to alcohol.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features
(not the main feature(s) of interest)?

Other interesting finding is that fixed acidity is strongly positively correlated to fixed acidity, establishing an unexpected discovery.

What was the strongest relationship you found?

The strongest relationship is between citric.acid and fixed.acidity.

Multivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the
investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of

looking at your feature(s) of interest?

  • There is no single clear relationship that explains what makes a wine have a good quality. Yet there is a pattern that lower quality wine tends to fall in section with density between 0.995 and 1.000 and alcohol between 9 and 10.

  • Through multivariate plot, we can see density and fixed density strengthened each other. Across all quality groups, higher density is related to higher fixed acidity, which makes sense because the more stable acid stays in wine, the more dense it is.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?

One interesting interaction is the plot of pH vs density with color of quality since I expected that certain combination of pH and density would contribute to a quality of wine. However, quality is pretty dispersed across the plot.

OPTIONAL: Did you create any models with your dataset? Discuss the
strengths and limitations of your model.

I create a linear model to predict quality. However, the highest R^2 is only 0.264, which means linear model might not be a good metrics for predicting the quality of wine. However, some useful information can be fetched. Among all the features in the model, pH improves the model by the most extent. ——

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One

Description One

The distribution of total sulfur dioxide appears to be bimodal on log scale.
Perhaps, wines are divided into two ranges to sulfur dioxide amount. There is also an gap in the upper range between 5 and 5.5.

Plot Two

Description Two

We see that fixed.acidity has a moderate positive relationship between density. This raises interesting questions about what determines the density of a wine. Fixed.acidity might be a good component.

Plot Three

Description Three

We see lower quality wine tends to fall in section with density between 0.995 and 1.000 and alcohol between 9 and 10. This means low quality wine could be associated with high density and low alcohol. This points to an interesting speculation that high density might contain other unnecessary chemicals without the presence of high alcohol. ——

Reflection

Given that I already learned R in school, I didn’t find much trouble getting used to the syntax. However, I had moments struggling with choosing what plots to use, how to understand what makes a wine high quality. I also found it difficult to design the plots to emphasize certain patterns in the data.
There are many interetsing insights found in the exploration. For instances, the fixed.acidity is positively related to citric acid, yet negatively related to volatile acid. Both fixed and citric acid are negatively related to pH. Moreover, fixed acid is closely related to density. The higher the fixed acid, the higher the density.   However, I have trouble finding a variable that is closely related to quality even after log transformation. Yet I still find that low quality wine is associated with low alcohol and high density. Further exploration might need bigger dataset with more features to study what makes a good wine. For example, does other substance like Glycerol or Amino Acids contribute to the quality. Moreover, does certain ratio of substance like sugar and fixed acid ratio have high correlation with the quality of wine?
